occurrences.line_text: And if that either to that shield had right,
That victory they dare not wish to either side.
If either salues, or oyles, or herbes, or charmes
On either side disparted with his rod,
And that more wondrous was, in either iaw
Either for grieuous shame, or for great teene,
That her on either side do sore assay,
With either of those knights on euen coast,
But either hellish feends, or powres on hie:
He either enuying my toward good,
So both attonce him charge on either side,
On either side, that neither mayle could hold,
That either me too bold ye weene, this wise
Matchable either to Semiramis,
To be no earthly wight, but either Spright,
His Beast he felly prickt on either syde,
But either Gloriana let her chuse,
And either vowd with all their power and wit,
Vnwares haue prest: for either fatall end,
That either seemes some cursed witches deed,
And girt in with two walles on either side;
Either for want of handsome time and place,
Either fast closed in some hollow greaue,
And with a shaft was shot through either eye,
Matchable either to that ympe of Troy,
In loue were either ended or begunne:
Should either winne him one, or lye without the dore.
But either he should neither of them haue, or both.
So furiously they met, that either bare
Full many mightie strokes on either side
But either sdeignes with other to partake:
Ne either car'd to ward, or perill shonne,
Ne either cared life to saue or spill,
For either they were left vppon the land,
For either doth on other much relie.
Then either care of parents could refraine,
Either through gifts, or guile, or such like waies,
And either beat him in, or driue him out.
On either side of her, two young men stood,
Therefore on either side she was sustained
That ill perhaps mote fall to either side.
And each of either take his share aright.
And either both them drownes, or trayterously slaies.
Either the other from his steede to cast;
And all the sea, deuided each from either:
Either by being wreckt vppon the sands,
Ne either sought the others strokes to shun,
Together met, and strongly either strooke
Either embracing other louingly,
And swearing faith to either on his blade,
But either others cause to maintaine mutually.
He either spoiles, if they against him stand,
Either the Prince in peeces to haue torne
As either might for wealth haue gotten bene,
On either part, she placed th'one on th'one,
Past through his shield, & pierst through either syde,
Either for fame, or else for exercize,
Either to daunce, when they to daunce would faine,
That she thereby mote either freely wend,
But either blotted them with infamie,
And helmets hewen deepe, shew marks of eithers might.
And deadly points at eithers breast to bend,
And with them eke, O Goddesse heauenly bright,
And this faire couple eke to shroud the[m]selues were fain.
Making her death their life, and eke her hurt their good.
And eke the Graces seemed all to sing,
And eke themselues too rudely rigorous,
Vp Vna rose, vp rose the Lyon eke,
His fair enchaunted steed, and eke his charmed launce.
And eke my night of death the shadow is;
And eke th'enchaunter ioyous seemd no lesse,
Through shield and bodie eke he should him beare:
And eke with fatnesse swollen were his eyne,
And eke vnhable once to stirre or go,
A vile disease, and eke in foote and hand
And eke the verse of famous Poets witt
Of brothers prayse, to you eke longs his loue.
And eke enchaunted armes, that none can perce,
And eke wyld roring Buls he would him make
His wearie limbes vpon: and eke behind,
These eyes did see that knight both liuing and eke ded.
And eke this battels end, will need another place.
The ground eke groned vnder him for dreed;
Who haplesse, and eke hopelesse, all in vaine
And eke so faint in euery ioynt and vaine,
Of wondrous worth, and eke of wondrous mights,
So thought I eke of him, and thinke I thought aright.
And eke impatient of vnwonted paine,
And eke the fruitfull-headed beast, amaz'd
Your fortune maister eke with gouerning,
And eke her feete most monstrous were in sight;
And eke as pledges firme, right hands together ioynd.
And eke from whom make ye this hasty flight:
Where iustice growes, there grows eke greater grace,
But all the good is Gods, both power and eke will.
But simple true, and eke vnfained sweet,
And eke huge mountaines from their natiue seat
And made him pray both earely and eke late:
Him dearely kist, and fairely eke besought
To be both gratious, and eke liberall:
And eke a litle Hermitage thereby,
And eke be safe from daunger far descryde:
And eke the pennes, that did his pineons bynd,
And th'English Bath, and eke the german Spau,
And life eke euerlasting did befall:
Another like faire tree eke grew thereby,
There eke my feeble barke a while may stay,
Both daughter and eke kingdome, lo I yield to thee.
And eke himselfe had craftily deuisd
Came with them eke, all were they wondrous loth,
And giue you eke good helpe to their decay,
And eke of surest steele, that may be found,
And eke her face ill fauourd, full of wrinckles old.
And eke the Hag with many a bitter threat,
Loue that two harts makes one, makes eke one will:
And eke the faith, which she to me did bynd;
She comes vnsought, and shonned followes eke.
Pyrrochles was, and grieued eke entyre;
His mother eke, more to augment his spight,
And weetlesse eke of lately wrought despight,
Art Lord, and eke of nature Soueraine,
Him followed eke Sir Guyon euermore,
Here eke that famous golden Apple grew,
And eke blaspheming heauen bitterly,
The Porter eke to her did lout with humble gestes.
And eke emongst them litle Cupid playd
But somwhat sad, and solemne eke in sight,
Sir Guyon chaunst eke on another booke,
Of stature huge, and eke of courage bold,
And eke that ample Pit, yet farre renownd,
But both her selfe, and eke her daughter deare,
And eke in semblance of his puissance great,
In rule succeede, and eke in fathers prayse;
And Hengist eke soone brought to shamefull death.
With him the Palmer eke in habit sad,
She eke so often, as his life decayd,
And eke the fairest Alma met him there
Such vertue in his staffe had eke this Palmer sage.
And eke the gate was wrought of substaunce light,
So did he eke Sir Guyon passing by:
And eke her louer stroue: but all in vaine;
Then led they her away, and eke that knight
And eke the Prince like treaty handeled,
Through countries waste, and eke well edifyde,
And eke through feare as white as whales bone:
And eke those six, which lately with her fought,
And eke the Redcrosse knight ran to the stownd,
Her succourd eke the Champion of the bloudy Crosse.
And eke the Redcrosse knight gaue her good aid,
That now we foolish men that prayse gin eke t'enuy.
And euery riuer eke his course forbeares
Ah Nurse, what needeth thee to eke my paine?
And darkesome night he eke could turne to day:
And eke enrooted deepe must be that Tree,
Of Britons eke with him attonce shall dye;
Bad eke attonce their charets to be sought;
And eke himselfe mournd at their mournfull plight,
With no lesse haste, and eke with no lesse dreed,
Foule horror, and eke hellish dreriment:
His steed eke seem'd t'apply his steps to his intent.
And eke thy selfe of honour, which thou didst atchiue.
And eke the gentle shepheard swaynes, which sat
And after them her selfe eke with her went
And eke attonce the heauy trees they clime,
And eke himselfe her cruelly exyld:
And aboue many knights is eke esteemed,
Which when she saw, more bent to eke my smartes,
And Panope her entertaind eke well,
And eke reward the wretch for his mesprise,
And eke their lately bruzed parts to bring in plight.
And eke that straunger knight emongst the rest;
Wedlock contract in bloud, and eke in blood
His worke great Troynouant, his worke is eke
So doth he punish her and eke himselfe torment.
And Hellenors both eyes did eke beguyle,
And eke my selfe, albe I simple such,
And eke thy words vncourteous and vnkempt;
And eke Sir Paridell, all were he deare;
And after him eke fearefull Trompart sped;
And eke through likenesse of his gotish beard,
And eke all Cupids warres they did repeate,
He loued eke Iphimedia deare,
So proou'd it eke that gracious God of wine,
He fild with Hylas name; the Nymphes eke Hylas cryde.
And eke the Ladie selfe he brought away,
And eke fayre Amoret now freed from feare,
And eke of priuate persons many moe,
And as her eares so eke her feet were odde,
And eke because his loue he wonne by right:
And eke vnto her lookes a law she made,
And eke thy childrens thrids to be asunder burst.
And eke so short, that seemd their ends out shortly came.
And tribute eke withall, as to his Soueraine.
And eke those masked Ladies riding them beside.
And Ate eke prouokt him priuily,
But him likewise with that same speare he eke did quell.
But by his friend himselfe eke soone he fond,
And eke of honour she did him forestall.
And eke with these, full many other Knights
And he himselfe his right would eke releasse:
And eke the breathfull bellowes blew amaine,
Her feeble ioynts layd eke a downe to rest;
And with him eke that aged Squire attone;
And eke defiled with foule villanie
And eke in stature higher by a span,
And eke his garment, to be thereto meet,
And eke by that he saw on euery tree,
And eke his deare companion of his care.
And eke all mindlesse of his owne deare Lord
And eke his caue, in which they both were bond:
And eke that age despysed nicenesse vaine,
And eke the Doue sate by the Faulcons side,
And eke through heauie armes, which sore annoyd
And eke too loose of life, and eke of loue too light.
And eke too loose of life, and eke of loue too light.
And eke the Prince, when as he them auized,
And eke of Lordship, with both land and fee:
So eke lou'd Blandamour, but yet at pleasure
And eke the famous prize of beauty from them wonne.
And eke the loue of Ladies foule defame;
And th'other eke his malice did empeach,
And eke an hundred brasen caudrons bright,
Begets and eke conceiues, ne needeth other none.
Yet all the rest were eke her equall peares,
And eke he somewhat seem'd to stoupe afore
The Doune & eke the Frith, both which prepard her way.
And eke the Bull hath with his bow-bent horne
And some by sleight he eke doth vnderfong.
And eke the courser, whereuppon he rad,
And eke their dame halfe dead did hide her self for feare.
And eke her feete, those feete of siluer trye,
Both her and eke all others to excell:
Soone after eke came she, with fell intent,
And eke with gratefull seruice me right well apay.
And eke pursew, if he attaine it may.
And eke of powre her owne doome to vndo,
And eke the knight attonce she did betray:
And then both Knights enuide, & Ladies eke did spight.
Both armed Knights, and eke vnarmed rout:
And eke his steedes like to an hungry hound,
And eke the fastnesse of his dwelling place,
And eke the rocke, in which he wonts to dwell,
To whom she eke inclyning her withall,
And eke all strangers in that region
And eke her selfe through sudden strange affright,
There eke he placed a strong garrisone,
Both through his haberieon, and eke his corse:
And eke him selfe did threaten to confound,
Thereto a great aduauntage eke he has
And eke to th'earth his burden with him bare:
Now when they saw it falne, they eke him greeted all.
And eke that Idoll deem'd so costly dere;
And eke Grantortoes worthy punishment.
And eke her champions glorie sounded ouer all.
But this same both her selfe, and others eke perplext.
And eke that Lady his faire louely lasse.
And eke the Lady was full faire to see,
But both himselfe reuil'd, and eke his loue;
And eke the Ladie fearefully aghast,
So did Decetto eke him circumuent,
And eke this Squire, who likewise wounded was
And with him eke the saluage, that whyleare
And eke could doe, as well as say the same,
And eke the biting of that harmefull Beast
And eke his Lady, though she sickely were,
And eke his Dame him seeing in such guize,
And eke thy selfe, for want of manly hart,
And eke all knights hast shamed with this knightlesse part.
And eke desirous of the offred meed,
He glad of life, and willing eke to wreake
And where is eke your friend, which halfe it ought?
Him thether eke for all his fearefull threat
And if he hungry were, him offred eke to eat.
But her did honour, and eke many a one
And eke but hardly seene by candle-light:
What mister men, and eke from whence they were.
Some whet their kniues, and strip their elboes bare:
With that vpleaning on her elbow weake,
And leaning on his elbow, these few wordes let fly.
And as in hate of honorable eld,
As feeling wondrous comfort in her weaker eld.
And that weake eld hath left thee nothing wise,
Ne suffred them to perish through long eld,
In which he dyde, made ripe for death by eld,
O cursed Eld the cankerworme of writs,
And almost blind through eld, that scarce her way could see.
Hate was the elder, Loue the younger brother;
Then th'elder, and him maystred still in all debate.
No lesse then do her elder sisters broode.
To whom the elder did this aunswere frame;
Then turning to the elder thus he sayd;
The one of them, that elder did appeare,
Yet was that other swayne this elders syre,
The eldest of three brethren, all three bred
His eldest brother, burning all with rage
The eldest two most sober, chast, and wise,
Of which the eldest, that Fidelia hight,
The first of them that eldest was, and best,
The eldest did against the youngest goe,
He that made loue vnto the eldest Dame,
Elissa (so the eldest hight) did deeme
The eldest Gonorill gan to protest,
He had two sonnes, whose eldest called Lud
The first and eldest, which that scepter swayd,
The eldest brother did vntimely dy;
His line, which is the eldest of the three,
The whilest their eldest brother was away,
Cupid their eldest brother; he enioyes
Of all which Nereus th'eldest, and the best,
The eldest of the which was slaine erewhile
Therefore these two, her eldest sonnes she sent,
With thousand spots of colours queint elect,
Oft chaunging sides, and oft new place electing,
That might haue had of life or death election:
And trampling the fine element, would fiercely rampe.
Her flitting partes, and element vnsound,
His neighbour element in his reuenge:
Of Mulcibers deuouring element;
Makes the huge element against her kind
That cruell element, which all things feare,
More great then th'eares of Elephants by Indus flood.
Euen thrise eleuen descents the crowne retaynd,
But Elfant was of most renowmed fame,
Then Elfar, who two brethren gyants kild,
Which when the valiant Elfe perceiu'd, he lept
Till morrow next, that I the Elfe subdew,
Which when the wakeful Elfe perceiu'd, streight way
Goe caytiue Elfe, him quickly ouertake,
But vanisht is. The Elfe him cals alowd,
And drawing nigh him said, Ah misborne Elfe,
And trees did tremble. Th'Elfe therewith astownd,
In great disdaine, he answerd; Hardy Elfe,
Vaine glorious Elfe (said he) doest not thou weet,
The warlike Elfe much wondred at this tree,
Thereat the Elfe did blush in priuitee,
That man so made, he called Elfe, to weet
The noble Elfe, and carefull Palmer drew
But that he by an Elfe was gotten of a Fay.
Ne did he spare (so cruell was the Elfe)
Taught to obay the menage of that Elfe,
Who was to weet a wretched wearish elfe,
Of a fresh streame I with that Elfe did play,
Thou foolishe Elfe (said then the Gyant wroth)
And Idols serues; so let his Idols serue the Elfe.
But Pastorella, wofull wretched Elfe,
He left two sonnes, of which faire Elferon
To Elfes, but sprong of seed terrestriall,
After all these Elficleos did rayne,
The wise Elficleos in great Maiestie,
But Elfiline enclosd it with a golden wall.
Vnto that Elfin knight he bad him fly,
But how long time, said then the Elfin knight,
But th'Elfin knight, which ought that warlike wage,
Him litle answerd th'angry Elfin knight;
And guiltie Elfin bloud shall sacrifice in hast.
With Elfin sword, most shamefully betrade?
The dreadlesse courage of this Elfin knight,
There when the Elfin knight arriued was,
And her base Elfin brood there for thee left.
To serue againe his soueraine Elfin Queene,
He was an Elfin borne of noble state,
Me list not (said the Elfin knight) receaue
But th'Elfin knight with wonder all the way
And rolles of Elfin Emperours,
Quick, the first authour of all Elfin kind:
Was Elfin; him all India obayd,
And high accompt throughout all Elfin land,
And all things quieted, the Elfin Knight
With th'Elfin Knight, her Ladies best beloued;
But th'Elfin swayne, that oft had seene like sight,
Vnto this place when as the Elfin Knight
That endlesse were to tell. The Elfin Knight,
Next him was noble Elfinan, who layd
His sonne was Elfinell, who ouercame
Soone as the Elfing knight in presence came,
Then Elfinor, who was in Magick skild;
How euer now accompted Elfins sonne,
And pitteous Elidure put in his sted;
Elissa (so the eldest hight) did deeme
And to my brother did ellope streight way:
The vine-prop Elme, the Poplar neuer dry,
Who with great wisedome, and graue eloquence
Strangle her, else she sure will strangle thee.
Shall vs restore, none else from hence may vs vnbynd.
Or if that any else did Ioue excell:
That knew not, whether right he went, or else astray.
Or else goe them auenge, and let be seene,
In medicine, that else hath to thee wonne
And all things else, the which his art did teach:
Thy guilty wrong, or else thee guilty yield.
Else should this Redcrosse knight in bands haue dyde,
O helpe Orgoglio, helpe, or else we perish all.
None else to death this man despayring driue,
Else had his sinnes so great, and manifold
For well she wist, his crime could else be neuer cleare.
Else neuer could the force of fleshly arme,
Or false or trew, or liuing or else dead,
Which else could not endure those beames bright,
Or else his wrong with greater puissance maintaine.
Else be ye sure he dearely shall abyde,
And all that else this worlds enclosure bace,
Else neuer should thy iudgement be so fraile,
Yet was there not with her else any one,
There is: else much more wretched were the cace
Or ought that else your honour might maintaine,
Else mote it needes downe to his manly brest
Which were it not, that I am else delaid
Not good nor seruiceable else for ought,
But if ought else that I mote not deuise,
As all things else, the which this world doth weld,
Nought else, but treason, from the first this la[n]d did foyle.
All those, and all that else does horrour breed,
Else she will slip away, and all our drift despise.
For nothing else might keepe her safe and sound;
Or else with vs by dint of sword approue,
And what so else his person most may vaunt?
Yet these, and all that else had puissaunce,
For else my feeble vessell crazd, and crackt
And all that else was pretious and deare,
Lifteth it vp, that else would lowly fall:
Else shall thy louing Lord thee see no more,
She gan auize, where else he mote him hyde:
Or else for feare of shame and fowle disgrace.
And seeke else without hazard of thy hed.
He else could doe, he saw himselfe esteemd,
For perdie else how mote it euer bee,
May her perhaps containe, that else would algates fleet.
Or else for shame, so fowle reproch to shonne,
As if they lay in wait, or else themselues did hide.
And all that else the vaine world vaunten may,
What is there else, but cease these fruitlesse paines,
From doing him to dy. For else her paine
This doe and liue, else die vndoubtedly.
Released her, that else was like to sterue,
Else how could one of equall might with most,
The rest them selues in troupes did else dispose,
Which else was like to haue bene lost, and bore
But it would loose, or else a sunder teare.
Shall else be told in order, as it fell.
Or else vnweeting, what it else might bee;
Or else vnweeting, what it else might bee;
Shall death be th'end, or ought else worse, aread.
Or else some woodman shrowded there from scorching sunne.
Full many did affray, that else faine enter would.
Yet all those sights, and all that else I saw,
Nor all that else through all the world is named
Else would the waters ouerflow the lands,
So all things else, that nourish vitall blood,
Whose like none else could shew, the which they Ruffins call.
As all things else in time are chaunged quight.
Or else by ordele, or by blooddy fight;
Else he doth hold him backe or beat away.
The right or wrong, the false or else the trew?
Or else two falses, of each equall share;
Else should afflicted wights oftimes despeire.
Whether by might extort, or else by slight deceaued.
Or else by wracke, that wretches hath distrest,
Or else what other deadly dismall day
Might else haue with felicitie bene crowned:
For else he sure had left not one aliue,
Nor of ought else, that may be richest red,
To whom nought else, but bare life doth remaine,
What else they haue, is all the Tyrants fee;
Else should he thrise haue needed, for the nonce
What is there else (sayd he) left of their rout?
To Faery Court, where what him fell shall else be told.
Till I him ouertake, or else subdew:
Good Knights and Ladies true, and many else destroyd.
And whatsoeuer else he would requere.
Himselfe to yeeld his loue, or else to fight.
Or had no courage, or else had no gall.
Being vnhable else alone to ride;
The perill of his pride, or else be ouerrun.
Both horse and armes, and what so else to lend,
Or what so else were vnto him betyde:
Or else remained in most wretched state,
Either for fame, or else for exercize,
For else his feare could not be satisfyde.
Else had he surely there bene slaine, or fowlyshent.
Or else abide the death, that hard before you stands.
Or else to course about their bases light;
As was in all the lond of Faery, or elsewheare.
Or wants she health, or busie is elsewhere?
By further search had passage found elsewhere,
Then of my skill: who helpe may haue elsewhere,
As ye may elsewhere read that ruefull history.
When chaunst Malbecco busie be elsewhere,
Would needes depart, as shall declared be elsewhere.
Whilest his faire Pastorella was elsewhere,
Such vgly monstrous shapes elswhere may no man reed.
Saue in this Paradise, be heard elswhere:
That since their days such louers were not found elswhere.
And did right noble deedes, the which elswhere are showne.
Had from their maisters fled, & now sought hyre elswhere.
And all the moore twixt Eluersham and Dell,
Th'off-spring of Elues and Faries there he fond,
Th'Elysian fields, and liue in lasting blesse,
That she to them vouchsafed to embace
And softly can embalme on euery side.
My tender sides in this rough rynd embard,
